==English==
{{wikipedia|She (disambiguation)}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|sche}}, {{m|enm|scho}}, {{m|enm|hyo}}, {{m|enm|Èho|t=she}}, whence also Yorkshire dialectal {{m|en|shoo|t=she}}, {{cog|sco|she}}, {{m|sco|sho|t=she}}.

Probably from {{inh|en|ang|hÄ“o}}<ref name="CHEL">{{cite-book|en|year=1992|title=Cambridge History of the English Language|chapter=Phonology and Morphology|volume=II|editor=Norman Blake|author=Roger Lass|pages=118-119}}</ref><ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|she|pos=''pron.Â¹, n., and adj.''|id=177685|noformat=1|date=September 2013}}</ref> (whence dialectal {{cog|en|hoo}}), with an irregular change in stress from ''hÄ“o'' to ''heÅ'' {{IPAchar|/hjoË/}}, then a development from {{IPAchar|/hj-/}} to {{IPAchar|/Ã§/}} to {{IPAchar|/Êƒ-/}},<ref name="Fulk"/><ref name="Clark"/> similar to the derivation of ''Shetland'' from {{m+|non|Hjaltland}}. In this case, ''she'' is from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hiju}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hijÅ||this, this one|g=f}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*á¸±e-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*á¸±ey-||this, here}}, and is cognate with {{cog|stq|jo}}, {{m|stq|ju}}, {{cog|fy|hja}}, {{cog|frr|jÃ¼}}, {{cog|da|hun}}, {{cog|sv|hon}}; more at {{m|en|he}}.

A derivation from {{cog|ang|sÄ“o|t=the or that", occasionally "she}} is also possible, though less likely.<ref name="OED"/><ref name="Fulk">{{cite-book|author=R. D. Fulk|title=An Introduction to Middle English: Grammar and Texts|year=2012|pages=64-65}}</ref><ref name="Clark">Cecily Clark, ''The Peterborough Chronicle, 1070-1154'' (1970), page lxvi-lxvii: "Most favoured recently has been derivation from ''heo''/''hie'', though a chain of development [hi] > [hj] > [Ã§] > [Êƒ]. The decisive change [Ã§] > [Êƒ] has been various explained, either as an example of a Norse sound-change found elsewhere only in a few place-names (the so-called "Shetland theory") or as substitution of a common initial phoneme for a rare one, linked with the need to maintain the distinction both from masculine ''he'' and from second-person plural ''Èe''. Geographical distribution of''h-'' and ''sch-'' forms during the Middle English period is said to support derivation from stress-shifted [hjÃ¨]. [... There] still seems, however, something to be said for the older theory put forward in ''NED'': that ''scÃ¦'' developed from ''sie'', through [sjÃ¨]. Certainly the demonstrative ''seo'' was used as an emphatic pronoun, as, for instance, in ''Sermo in Festis S. Marie''; and, although the variant nom. sing. ''sie'' is regularly used only in the ''Vespasian Psalter Gloss'' (once in ''Rushworth St. Matthew''), such forms as ''sy ea'' in the E Preface (beside DF ''seo'') and ''si [...]'' in the ''Northhamptonshire Geld-Roll'' suggest that it may have been current in Peterborough usage as well. This theory explains better than that of derivation from stress-shifted ''heo''/''hie'' the coexistence of ''sch-'' and ''h-''forms in the same text, as in ''Sir Gawain'' (''scho'' and ''ho'') and ''William of Palerne'' (''sche'' and ''he''). Its weakness lies in failing to explain why the [Êƒ], regular in the pronoun, never occurs in the demonstrative [...]"</ref> In that case, {{m|ang|sÄ“o}} would have undergone a change in stress from ''sÄ“o'' to ''seÅ'' {{IPAchar|/sjoË/}}, then a change from {{IPAchar|/sj-/}} to {{IPAchar|/Êƒ-/}}, similar to the derivation of ''sure'' from {{m+|fro||seur}}.<ref name="Clark"/><ref name="Wardale">E. E. Wardale, ''An Introduction to Middle English'' (1937 [2016]), chapter VI (pp. 91-92 and notes), covers other proposed explanations, including that it is from a mixture of both {{m|ang|hÄ“o}} and {{m|ang|sÄ“o}}</ref> It would then be cognate to {{cog|nl|zij}} and {{cog|de|sie}}.

Neither etymology would be expected to yield the modern [[vocalism]] in {{IPAchar|/iË/}} (the expected form would be {{m|en|shoo|id=she}}, which is in fact found dialectally). It may be due to influence from {{m|en|he}},<ref name="CHEL"/> but both {{m|ang|hÄ“o}} and {{m|ang|sÄ“o}} also have rare variants ({{m|ang|hÄ«e}} and {{m|ang|sÄ«e}}) that may give modern English {{IPAchar|/iË/}}.<ref name="Clark"/><ref>{{R:ang:Dictionary of Old English|hÄ“, hÄ“o, hit|E17157}}</ref>

