===Etymology 1===
{{etymon|en|id=pronoun|inh|enm>Ã¾ei>they|tree=1}}
{{root|en|ine-pro|*sÃ³}} From {{inh|en|enm|Ã¾ei}}, borrowed in the 1200s from {{der|en|non|Ã¾eir}},<ref name="AHD">{{R:American Heritage Dictionary}}</ref> plural of the demonstrative {{m|non|sÃ¡}} which acted as a plural pronoun. Displaced native {{ncog|enm|he}} from {{ncog|ang|hÄ«e}} â€” which vowel changes had left indistinct from {{m|enm|he||he}} â€” by the 1400s,<ref name="AHD"/><ref>{{R:Etymonline}}</ref><ref>Otto Jespersen, ''Growth and Structure of the English Language''</ref> being readily incorporated alongside native words beginning with the same sound ({{m|en|the}}, {{m|en|that}}, {{m|en|this}}). Used as a singular pronoun since 1300,<ref name="AHD"/> e.g. in the 1325 ''Cursor Mundi''<!--(which uses ''[[their|Ã¾er]]'')-->.

The Norse term (whence also {{cog|is|Ã¾eir||they}}, {{cog|fo|teir|t=they}}, {{cog|da|de||they}}, {{cog|sv|de||they}}, {{cog|nn|dei||they}}) is from {{der|en|gem-pro|*Ã¾ai||those}} (from {{der|en|ine-pro|*sÃ³|*to-|that}}), whence also {{cog|ang|Ã¾Ä||those}} (whence obsolete English {{dbt|en|tho|notext=1}}), {{cog|sco|thae}}, {{m|sco|thai}}, {{m|sco|thay||they; those}}.

The origin of the determiner {{m|en|they||the, those}} is unclear. The ''OED'', ''English Dialect Dictionary'' and ''Middle English Dictionary''<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=thei|pos=pron|id=MED45106|accessdate=2016-01-28}}</ref> define it and its Middle English predecessor {{m|enm|thei}} as a demonstrative determiner or adjective meaning "those" or "the". This could be a continuation of the use of the English pronoun {{m|en|they}}'s Old Norse etymon {{m|non|Ã¾eir}} as a demonstrative meaning "those", but the ''OED'' and ''EDD'' say it is limited to southern, especially southwestern, England, specifically outside the region of Norse contact.

